1. The Core Realization (Wasted Silicon)
When your dataset contains low-range numbers (like a maximum value of 5), you only need 3 bits (1012 ) of data to represent any given number.
In a standard application program, developers default to using a standard 32-bit integer (int). In our matrix sandbox, this means that for every single element, 29 out of the 32 bits inside your memory storage are just zeros. You are essentially using a massive freight truck to transport a single envelope, causing a massive waste of physical memory bandwidth and cache space.
2. The Arithmetic Friction of Custom Bitfields
Your immediate intuition was to pack those 3-bit spaces tightly back-to-back inside memory, which would mathematically allow you to squeeze 42 integers into a single 128-bit hardware container.
However, the hardware architecture creates a friction point here: modern CPU execution units do not have native, hardwired circuits to add or multiply 3-bit boundaries. If you store them this way, the CPU has to execute multiple low-level bitwise shift (>>) and mask (&) instructions to isolate, extract, and unpack each element before it can perform the matrix multiplication. The processing overhead of constantly unpacking the data destroys any performance gained from saving memory space.
3. The Co-Design Compromise: 8-Bit Quantization
To get the maximum theoretical throughput without paying the "unpacking tax," the optimal approach is to compromise on the nearest physical hardware boundary supported by the M4's vector units: 8-bit integers (int8_t / char).
An 8-bit memory slot easily covers your 3-bit data requirements (storing unsigned values up to 255), meaning you stop wasting 24 bits of zeros per number. More importantly, 8-bit elements are natively understood by the ARM64 pipeline.
4. Quadrupling Vector Processing Density
By shifting the matrix design to 8-bit data boundaries, you change how the physical 128-bit vector registers handle the data footprint:
* Instead of slicing the register into four 32-bit lanes (.4s logic), the M4 handles the register as sixteen independent 8-bit lanes (.16b logic).
* When the hardware clock cycle ticks, the internal arithmetic execution unit launches 16 parallel calculations simultaneously across those isolated lanes instead of just 4.
5. Architectural Impact on the Memory Wall
By reducing the data footprint of your matrices by 75% (dropping from 4 bytes per number down to 1 byte), you instantly multiply the effective capacity of your M4's L1 and L2 caches. Individual data tiles hold four times as many elements, dramatically reducing the frequency of high-latency round-trips to the main RAM and keeping the computing units saturated at peak operational speed.
